## Workflow

### Structure linking
I have a "Home" Doc which is basically the home page of my documents, the idea being you can reach everywhere from that page and you can always backlink back to the home page.
New Docs usually have a backlink at the top which links back to its "parent" document as well as tags to group pages together

### Tags
I haven't decided which I prefer yet but I have a mix of these tag formats:

#### Hidden tag
`%% #Tag %%`

#### Frontmatter header
```
---
someVariable: Foo
tags: These Are All Seperate Tags
---
```
This option being a frontmatter and also showing a nicely formatted header for the doc, its also a space you can add variables which can be used in dataview

![Pasted image 20220510142447.png](data:image/png;base64,)

### Structured MOCs
If I have a topic I'm writing docs for I'll create a group for that topic i.e. "Projects" and create a document called "Project MOCs". MOC stands for "Maps of Content" the idea being that its a place which you can find all project related docs.
I usually auto generate these using dataview and search for all projects with the `#project` tag and you can do some other interesting interesting things like adding in variables to give the state of a project.

### Daily notes
Daily notes are generated by templator and contain Notes, Tasks, Daily Puzzles

#### Daily log
I have daily log which I write up anything I feel I want to remember about something I've done in the day and link out to topics which are going to come up in future i.e. about something I was doing with a database and link to a page and subheading on the query which I have used.

#### Tasks
Tasks that are due today, tomorrow and new tasks. Also what I have completed today

#### Daily puzzles
Wordle, Heardle, Moviedl...

## Templates
I make template files and store them in a "Templates" directory
Template files for anything I am going to do more than once and want some kind structure to, most are pretty specific to my needs but the "DailyNoteTemplate" is useful and is something I found online but have tailored to my own needs. 
The template below needs templator to work with things like creation date or anything with `tp.`

### DailyNoteTemplate (escaped)
```
---

creation date: <% tp.file.creation_date() %>

tags: DailyNote <% tp.file.title.split('-')[0] %>

---

modification date: <%+ tp.file.last_modified_date("dddd Do MMMM YYYY HH:mm:ss") %> 

# <% tp.file.title %>

<< [[<% tp.date.now("YYYY-MM-DD", -1, tp.file.title, "YYYY-MM-DD") %>]] | [[<% tp.date.now("YYYY-MM-DD", 1, tp.file.title, "YYYY-MM-DD") %>|<% tp.date.now("YYYY-MM-DD", 1, tp.file.title, "YYYY-MM-DD") %>]]>>
